60|$|The <b>peloric</b> {{flowers of}} Pelargonium have their five petals {{in all respects}} alike, {{and there is no}} nectary so that they {{resemble}} the symmetrical flowers of the closely allied genus Geranium; but the alternate stamens are also sometimes destitute of anthers, the shortened filaments being left as rudiments, and in this respect they resemble the symmetrical flowers of the closely allied genus Erodium. Hence we may look at the <b>peloric</b> flowers of Pelargonium as having reverted to the state of some primordial form, the progenitor of the three closely related genera of Pelargonium, Geranium, and Erodium.|$|E
60|$|Antirrhinum majus (<b>peloric</b> var.).--This {{variety is}} quite fertile when artificially fertilised {{with its own}} pollen, but is utterly sterile when left to itself and uncovered, as humble-bees cannot crawl into the narrow tubular flowers.|$|E
60|$|Lastly, Linaria {{produces}} {{two kinds}} of <b>peloric</b> flowers, one having simple petals, and the other having them all spurred. The two forms, as Naudin remarks (26/20. 'Nouvelles Archives du Museum' tome 1 page 137.), not rarely occur on the same plant, {{but in this case}} the spurred form almost invariably stands on the summit of the spike.|$|E
